Numbers

#As there are lots of 1's let's see how often people scored 1's on average for A B and X (over all conditions)

#Create a subset of data with just the 1's in there
OnesR1 <- subset(train, train$responseR1 == 1)
OnesR2 <- subset(train, train$responseR2 == 1)
OnesR3 <- subset(train, train$responseR3 == 1)
#Take the sum of these ones over participants (as we want to know how often (on average) one participant scored a 1 for A, B or X)
SumOnesR1 <- aggregate(OnesR1$responseR1, list(OnesR1$jatosStudyResultId), sum)
SumOnesR2 <- aggregate(OnesR2$responseR2, list(OnesR2$jatosStudyResultId), sum)
SumOnesR3 <- aggregate(OnesR3$responseR3, list(OnesR3$jatosStudyResultId), sum)
#then take the mean
AvgOnesR1 <- mean(SumOnesR1$x)
AvgOnesR2 <- mean(SumOnesR2$x)
AvgOnesR3 <- mean(SumOnesR3$x)
AvgOnesR1
## [1] 12.07843
AvgOnesR2
## [1] 16.08929
AvgOnesR3
## [1] 7.111111

The average amount of 1’s given to A is 12, which is 25% of all trails.
The average amount of 1’s given to B is 16, which is 33,3% of all trials
And the average amount of 1’s given to X is 7, which is 14,6% of all trials.
You would expect that B is scored lower over all (as it’s the least predictive over all), and A to be scored higher over all, so have less 1’s than the rest. However what we see here is that X, the stimuli that always appears is actually scored 1 the least amount of times.

These t-test show exactly what we would expect. The diamond trials are always scored higher than the no diamond trials. That is except for B. This makes sense though, because, except for the 50-50 condition, B predicts an diamond outcome a lot less than the others. So here we would expect that people will start to score B lower overall, even on the trials where it does predict an allergic reaction.

#First getting the test phase data 
test <- dat[which(dat$Train_Test == "Test"),] 
test$responseR1[test$responseR1 == 999] <- NA
test$responseR2[test$responseR2 == 999] <- NA

#And also splitting them into the different phases
testP1 <- test[which(test$Cond == "Phase1"),]
testP2 <- test[which(test$Cond == "Phase2"),]
testP3 <- test[which(test$Cond == "Phase3"),]
testP12 <- test[which(test$Cond == "Phase1" | test$Cond == "Phase2"),]

Phase 1


This phase was in the same order for each participant. At first the cues from the first block were seen, then a new cue (together with X of the first block) and then those of the third block were seen. This time participants were asked how likely they thought these items would lead to outcome Y, with Y being either a diamond (which they’ve seen before) or a fossil (a new outcome)

Creating and preparing the data
